1. What is CRUD in REST?

CRUD stands for:

Create (POST): Add a new resource.
Read (GET): Retrieve existing resources.
Update (PUT/PATCH): Modify existing resources.
Delete (DELETE): Remove resources.

In REST, each operation maps to an HTTP method and a URL pattern.

2. Setting Up the Entity and Repository

Example Entity: User

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    private String name;
    private String email;

    // getters and setters
}

Example Repository

public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    // JpaRepository provides all basic CRUD methods
}


3. Implementing REST Endpoints
3.1. Create (POST)

Use POST to create a new resource.
The client sends the resource data in the request body.

Implementation:

@PostMapping("/users")
public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
    User savedUser = userRepository.save(user);
    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(savedUser);
}

3.2. Read (GET)

Theory:
Use GET to retrieve resources.
You can get all resources or a specific one by ID.

Implementation:

// Get
 all users
@GetMapping("/users")
public List<User> getAllUsers() {
    return userRepository.findAll();
}

// Get user by ID
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
    return userRepository.findById(id)
        .map(user -> ResponseEntity.ok(user))
        .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
}


3.3. Update (PUT, PATCH)
Theory:
Use PUT to fully update a resource (replace all fields).
Use PATCH to partially update a resource (only some fields).

Implementation:

// Full update with PUT
@PutMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User userDetails) {
    return userRepository.findById(id)
        .map(user -> {
            user.setName(userDetails.getName());
            user.setEmail(userDetails.getEmail());
            User updatedUser = userRepository.save(user);
            return ResponseEntity.ok(updatedUser);
        })
        .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
}

// Partial update with PATCH (example: only email)
@PatchMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> updateUserEmail(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody Map<String, Object> updates) {
    return userRepository.findById(id)
        .map(user -> {
            if (updates.containsKey("email")) {
                user.setEmail((String) updates.get("email"));
            }
            User updatedUser = userRepository.save(user);
            return ResponseEntity.ok(updatedUser);
        })
        .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
}


3.4. Delete (DELETE)
Theory:

Use DELETE to remove a resource by ID.
Implementation:

@DeleteMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    return userRepository.findById(id)
        .map(user -> {
            userRepository.delete(user);
            return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
        })
        .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
}
4. How JpaRepository Helps

** JpaRepository** provides all basic CRUD methods: save(), findAll(), findById(), delete(), etc.

You don’t need to write SQL or custom queries for basic operations.
You can extend it with custom queries if needed.


